15 Nov 2019 12:19






No it would not.

The Earth has survived volcanic eruptions in the tens of thousands (or even hundreds of thousands) of megatons before (such as the Mount Tambora eruption in 1815, at an estimated 33,000MT), and at least one asteroid impact on the order of a hundred million megatons.

If you're looking to literally blow up the entire planet, you'll need somewhere in the neighborhood of 43 quadrillion megatons, although you'll certainly start causing significant problems for life on the surface well before then.





